":"okolo 1230","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, Anglie","Great Strickland, Westmorland, England":"Great Strickland, Westmorland, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1200–about 1278":"omkring 1200–omkring 1278","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1224–1303":"1224–1303","1227–Male":"1227–Afdød","1228–Male":"1228–Afdød","1176–1230":"1176–1230","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1228":"1228","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","about 1200":"omkring 1200","about 1278":"omkring 1278","about 1230":"omkring 1230","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Great Strickland, Westmorland, England":"Great Strickland, Westmorland, England"},"nl":{"about 1200–about 1278":"circa 1200–circa 1278","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1224–1303":"1224–1303","1227–Male":"1227–Overleden","1228–Male":"1228–Overleden","1176–1230":"1176–1230","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1228":"1228","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","about 1200":"circa 1200","about 1278":"circa 1278","about 1230":"circa 1230","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Great Strickland, Westmorland, England":"Great Strickland, Westmorland, England"},"en":{"about 1200–about 1278":"about 1200–about 1278","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1224–1303":"1224–1303","1227–Male":"1227–Deceased","1228–Male":"1228–Deceased","1176–1230":"1176–1230","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1228":"1228","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","about 1200":"about 1200","about 1278":"about 1278","about 1230":"about 1230","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Great Strickland, Westmorland, England":"Great Strickland, Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Strickland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from Great and Little Strickland (Westmorland) or Strickland Ketel and Strickland Roger (also Westmorland). The placenames derive from Old English <i>stīrc</i> ‘stirk, young bullock or heifer’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stricklen","meanings":["English: variant of   Strickland  ."]},{"name":"Stricklan","meanings":["English: variant of   Strickland  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","